
# StudyNotion — Full-Stack EdTech Platform

StudyNotion is a full‑stack educational platform built with JavaScript. It provides a modern, modular foundation for hosting courses, managing users and instructors, delivering lessons, running quizzes and assignments, and integrating payments and real‑time features for live classes and chats.

> NOTE: This README is a starting point. Update the environment variables, scripts, and deployment steps below to match this repository's actual structure (monorepo, separate `client`/`server` folders, or single app).

## Key features
- User authentication (students & instructors)
- Course creation and management (lessons, modules, resources)
- Video and content delivery (streaming or external embeds)
- Quizzes, assignments, grading, and progress tracking
- Payment integration for paid courses (Stripe/PayPal)
- Real-time features (chat, live classes / WebRTC)
- Admin dashboard and reporting
- Roles & permissions
- Notifications (email / in-app)

## Tech stack
- Language: JavaScript (frontend + backend)
- Frontend: React / Next.js (or plain React) — replace with actual framework used
- Backend: Node.js + Express (or other JS backend)
- Database: MongoDB / PostgreSQL (choose as used)
- Authentication: JWT / sessions
- Payments: Stripe / PayPal
- Realtime: Socket.IO or WebRTC
- Dev tooling: ESLint, Prettier, Jest (tests)

Adjust the list above to reflect the exact technologies used in this repo.

## Getting started (local development)

1. Clone the repo
   - git clone https://github.com/Koushikpali/StudyNotion---Full-Stack-Ed-Tech-Platform.git
   - cd StudyNotion---Full-Stack-Ed-Tech-Platform

2. Install dependencies
   - If the project is a monorepo with `client/` and `server/`:
     - cd server && npm install
     - cd ../client && npm install
   - If single project:
     - npm install

3. Configure environment variables
   - Copy the example env file:
     - cp .env.example .env
   - Edit `.env` with your credentials and keys (examples below).

4. Run the app (common patterns)
   - Server: npm run dev (or `npm start` / `nodemon src/index.js`)
   - Client: npm run dev (or `npm start` within `client/`)
   - If monorepo, you might use a root script like `npm run dev:all` to start both.

5. Build for production
   - Client: npm run build
   - Server: set NODE_ENV=production and start the server process manager (pm2, systemd, Docker)

## Example environment variables
Replace these with the actual variables used by the repo:
- PORT=4000
- MONGO_URI=mongodb+srv://<user>:<pass>@cluster0.mongodb.net/studynotion
- DATABASE_URL=postgres://user:pass@host:5432/studynotion
- JWT_SECRET=your_jwt_secret
- JWT_EXPIRES_IN=7d
- STRIPE_SECRET_KEY=sk_test_...
- STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET=whsec_...
- SMTP_HOST=smtp.example.com
- SMTP_PORT=587
- SMTP_USER=you@example.com
- SMTP_PASS=supersecret
- NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL=http://localhost:4000/api

